<br>
For the past several years, I've spent most of my time frustrated and spooked by just how scary the world at large was. Relatively small but very, very serious groups of people abusing power, people, and the planet in general. Every day, all day! It was like a Festival of Bad. Oddly, right around the time that the rest of the scary world did just what I was most afraid of and came knocking on my country's door I was finding myself alternately perplexed, outraged or simply terrified by the actions of the local bureaucracy moreso than the actions of some random crazed despot half a world away.<br>
<br>
Lately it's been getting worse. I absorb my daily doses of information as best I can, and my unease has done nothing but grow. I feel an odd sense of foreboding these days that I can't say I ever felt before. This isn't foreboding in the cataclysmic gloom and doom sense, it's much more of a &quot;We are <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>really</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> not in Kansas anymore, are we?&quot; kinda sense.<br>
<br>
Random bizarro ramblings on points of interest to me will now commence:<br>
<br>
American Airlines. Again. Yeah, the bossman resigned after the recent bit of publicity, but they're keeping the pension plan, Which is technically funded by taxpayer money since the company hasn't actually made any in years. I'm not seeing much return on this investment. Odd item to start with, but it's really been bugging me. Why is this company still in business again? And why am I paying to keep it that way? <br>
<br>
Santorum. A lot of people freaked out after the things he said. Oddly, I wasn't freaked out by what he said - I was horrified that people were taken by surprise, and even more so that absolutely nothing has come of it. Lott was a clue, people. And the representatives are the least of my worries, we have Federal Court appointees now that have repeatedly and deliberately used the power of their positions to leverage their personal beliefs upon society. I grew up thinking that courts enforced the will of the people, even if indirectly. I did not realize the objective had changed to enforcing their will on the people, directly. I would like them to please stop, forthwith.<br>
<br>
Betchel. Hey, maybe they can finally finish that chemical plant they were building for Hussien before he invaded Kuwait and we had to spank his bottom and place him firmly in the corner. Harkin is probably dying to get back to work on that pipeline that Saddam himself turned them down on because he thought he was getting the shaft. Cheney, Rumsfeld, Shultz, these are men possessed of very large and very sturdy balls. Possibly cast of solid brass.<br>
<br>
The Budget. We have now departed all known realms of mathematics and entered into the purely hypothetical. Please keep all hands, arms, and the ability to prove that 2 2 does indeed equal three hundred billion inside the vehicle until the ride has come to a complete stop.<br>
<br>
The Tax Cut. Yay! As best I can tell, the primary reason being peddled to promote a massive tax cut following a year of nearly unprecedented debt accumulation with no relief in sight not to mention a pesky little war to pay for is that this cut will promote economic stimulus and eventually pay for itself by creating 1.4 million jobs in 18 months. Well, the historical average is 2 million jobs created every 18 months in a recession without debt relief, so that's a pretty fucking safe bet eh? Not that the numbers really matter, since the Administration has already severely restricted access to information regarding these types of statistics in the future, via an Executive Order. What we don't know can't hurt the economy!<br>
<br>
With the introduction of the Patriot Act 2 (Pry Harder!) the Administration now formally supports the arrest of it's own citizens (not just citizens, the bill also provides a provision for foreign nationals and reserves the right to refuse extradition requests) with no access to due process and no formal charge. Who would be arrested is to be determined by single individuals whose identities are protected and reasoning is entirely withheld. It formally supports the detention of these individuals for indefinite periods at undisclosed locations. The existence of said detainees would be classified and releasing specific information about them would be a Federal crime. Note that this is already a practice in use, the new laws would simply make it legal. Well, it's already legal in places like China and Iran but we have yet to receive the official nod here.<br>
<br>
We've got some odd friends at the UN of late. Sudan, Iran, Pakistan, Libya, Algeria, Iraq (at least until we had to start bombing them) and the United States have been the primary proponents of alterations to documents regarding women's and children's rights around the world. Concerned Women for America would like to see language condemning the religon-specific infringements on women removed as it paints religion as a whole in a bad light. That wacky National Right to Life Committee wanted the phrase &quot;forced pregnancy&quot; removed from UN docs on women's rights because it could be reasonably used as an argument to promote abortions. I think we'd all be much happier if we just didn't count rapes by soldiers as a human rights violation, right? Especially if it saves a fetus or two! The State Department's annual report on human rights has condemned every single one of the countries joined with us in this noble endeavor as some of the worst rights violators in the world. When asked if finding herself chummed up with this odd bit of riff raff in front of a UN Rights Committee, Ellen Sauerbrey (Bush's chief representative to this commission) had this to say: &quot;I don't think we're aligning ourselves with countries who<br>
have bad records on human rights&quot;<br>
<br>
I'm about to start trying the ol' heel-click thing.<br>
