<br>
American Airlines didn't become the largest carrier in the world (which it still is) because they &quot;suck at what they do&quot;. They did so by offering the flying public what it wanted at the time. Until about three years ago, the industry favored a higher quality product (as opposed to the low-cost carriers) at higher price. When the economy (specifically, the tech industry) started it's decline, carriers like American and United started feeling the pinch and began changing their business practices to suit the new environment. The incidents surrounding September 11th basically tossed a huge monkey wrench in those plans by imposing higher fuel costs, higher security costs (of which only a small part was allowed by the government to be passed on to the consumer) and a frightened public. Not even Southwest has been able to avoid being hit by these effects. However, since they were already set up as a low-cost carrier, they were already in a position to come out of the crisis.<br>
<br>
I too live in Dallas and I don't know what &quot;street&quot; you live on, but the general consensus among people I know is that if American Airlines goes under, it will be extremely bad for the local economy because they are the largest employer in Fort Worth and rate pretty high in the entire region. If American goes under, the unemployment rate in the DFW area will skyrocket. That isn't even considering the loss of tax revenues, revenue generated by DFW airport and it's vendors, or the other industries that rose up to support the airline (Sabre/EDS, Aramark, etc).<br>
